<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Sitra</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Sitra</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">An introduction to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sitra</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sitra is uniquely placed to comment on the position of supported housing within the reformed welfare system. Sitra is the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">umbrella organisation commi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tted to raising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standards in the housing, care and support sector. We are a membership organisation and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a registered charity with over 25 years’ experience of offering practitioners a range of affordable policy, training, consultancy, information, conferen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce and capacity building services. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our membership comprises around 500 practitioner organisations in the field of housing with care and support. The membership elects the committee. Members are drawn from both providers and commissioners and from service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users, and from the statutory, voluntary and private sectors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We operate throughout England, and have offices in London, Birmingham and Southampton. Our work covers all aspects of supported housing, together with associated activities such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">human resourc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and staffing issues, financial management, and community care. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are recognised, funded and consulted by government departments and other bodies as representatives of providers of supported housing. We work with them on issues of national strategic si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gnificance for the sector. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recently we have been commissioned by the Department for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Communities and Local Government to conduct a small piece of research on Housing Benefit in supported and sheltered housing and this submission is substantially based on th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e findings of that research project, which have not yet been published</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Sitra bulletin is widely recognised as a key source of technical information and policy development news throughout the supported housing sector. With a circulation of around 3,5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> printed copies and additional on line views, it is the most widely distributed specialist publication within the supported housing sector. We supplement the bulletin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with regular briefings on matters relating to supported housing and its related fields. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sitra is also known as a leading training provider. Each year we train over 4,000 individuals across the country, either on our general programme or on tailored made inhouse courses for members and clients. We also provide a range of seminars and conferenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es on supported housing related themes. We estimate that over 2,000 people attend such a Sitra event each year. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are therefore in a unique position of combining a detailed knowledge of the housing related support sector on the ground with an understandi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng of and engagement with the developing national strategic agenda.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We welcome the opportunity to respond to the inquiry into the provision of support to meet housing costs in the reformed welfare system. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sitra is familiar with both the committee’s report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> highlighting in November on Universal Credit implementation: meeting the needs of vulnerable claimants and the subsequent Government response published in February 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Supported housing in England – Key points for the committee</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intended to:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Identify as comprehensively as possible all rented sector supported housing schemes in a small number of English local authorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Provide data that can be compared with existing datasets to identify the gaps in existing knowledge</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Provide refl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ections on the advantages and disadvantages of the approach taken, and the level of difficulty in forming a national picture.</span></li></ul><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The main focus of the research was on the numbers of people of working age living in supported and sheltered housing, and in parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cular the number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receiving Housing Benefit and the amounts they were receiving.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">research provides a robust picture of supported housing in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">six English housing authorities which we feel will be of great interest to the committee. As a specialis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t agency in the field of supported housing, we were able to use our extensive networks and understanding of the system to create the picture reflected in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the research.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our research looked only at supported housing within English authorities. We understand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that some work has been done using a similar format in Wales and Scotland, but are not clear how fare that work has progressed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, one of our strong learning points is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">publicly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">data sets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> do not either separately or in combina</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tion capture what supported housing there is in any area, who lives there and what it costs. Crucially this means policy makers cannot predict the consequences of measures they put forward as it is completely impossible for them to model their likely impac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have already seen this with Ministers now acknowledging the serious and unintended consequences for many supported housing projects of the household benefit cap, the social sector size criteria and the Unive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rsal C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">redit housing costs arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">What does supported housing look like</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our small sample of six English local authorities, we have been able to identify and study a total of 10,350 units of supported and sheltered housing. It can be seen that LA5 had almost three times as many units of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supported and sheltered housing as LA 1 so we should acknowledge immediately that LA 1 has the lowest population aged 16 and over of any of these six authorities. But the differences in numbers of units do not correlate with differences in population as ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n be seen in the table below.</span></li></ol><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:30.6pt; width:418.95pt"><tr style="height:31.5pt"><td style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:43.3pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="backgrou