; font-size:12pt">In LA3 and LA4 the two authorities for which we have HB data, we identified 223 working age occupants of sheltered housing for older people (including Extra Care sheltered housing):</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">150 in LA3 – 19% o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f the 792 occupants we identified</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">73 in LA4 – 14% of the 526 occupants we identified.</span></li></ul><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The importance of sheltered housing as a resource for people of working age with support needs can also be looked at by examining the number of working age HB claimants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in sheltered housing for older people. In LA1, we understood there were around 90 HB claimants of working age in sheltered housing for older people but there were only 25 units of supported housing for people of working age – and two of these were occupied</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by HB claimants of pension age!</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Children within supported housing </span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In LA3 and LA4 the two authorities for which we have HB data, we identified 60 children under the age of 16:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">34 in LA3, of whom 31 were in 20 units for women fleeing domestic violence</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">26 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in LA4, of whom 20 were in young people’s provision.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Overall, 37 of the 60 children we identified were in 33 units of domestic violence provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Pension age occupants of working age supported housing</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In LA3 and LA4 the two authorities for which we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HB data, we identified 206 occupants over pension age of supported housing primarily for people of working age. In both cases, they were mainly to be found in supported housing for people with mental health problems where they made up a significant proport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion of total occupants:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">88 out of 115 in LA3 – 25% of the 347 occupants we identified in supported housing for people with mental health problems </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">58 out of 91 in LA4 – 18% of the 320 occupants we identified in supported housing for people with mental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health problems.</span></li></ul><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In both authorities there were smaller numbers in supported housing for people with substance misuse problems, people with learning disabilities and single homeless people. In LA3 there were also three people over pension age in supported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">housing for people with physical disabilities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Assessment of exempt and non-exempt status</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There were only two local authorities, LA3 and LA4, where we can make a range of comparisons between the perceptions of exempt accommodation status of providers with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that of the HB department. The comparisons reflect the difficulty providers are facing in understanding the concept of exempt accommodation even though the rule has been in existence since January 1996.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For registered housing associations exempt accommodat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion status has rarely been of significance until a series of benefit changes began in April 2013 whereas for registered charities and not for profit organisations the status has long been crucial to the processing of their tenants’ HB claims. Not surprisin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gly, data from LA3 shows a marked difference in clarity about this status between providers of these two, different types.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The data from LA4 is striking because the level of uncertainty among providers seems to be almost matched by that of the HB departmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1 in 3 providers stated they do not know if their accommodation is exempt accommodation for HB purposes and a further nearly 1 in 3 expressed some level of uncertainty in assessing their status</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The HB department selected the option ‘do not know’ for 1 i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n 5 properties with many others remaining relatively uncertain.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Key learning points</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Key learning points from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> research include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 35.85pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The amount of supported housing in an area, the types of landlords and the levels of costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> vary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> significantly from one local authority to another. A local authority’s decision whether to retain its sheltered stock or transfer it to a provider registered with the HCA is the single most important factor determining the pattern of provision but is not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the only one.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 35.85pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The relative proportions of working age supported housing and of sheltered housing for old</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er people in authorities depend</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the level of provision for what were in the Supporting People programme called the “socially excluded” groups. Broadly speaking, provision for these groups has tended historically to be concentrated in major population centres.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 35.85pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is not a neat divi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sion between people of working age and people of pension age. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The proportion of people of working age living in sheltered housing for older people is higher than the proportion of people above pension age living in supported housing for people of working a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ge, as are the actual numbers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but there is a signficiant mix in many projects in all areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 35.85pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The cost of ordinary sheltered housing for older people is generally lower than the average costs of supported housing for other types of provision (including Extr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a Care sheltered housing)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This apart, there is no other consistent pattern of varying costs across client groups either in the degree of variation or the client groups that are most expensive.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 35.85pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current level of understanding of either providers or loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l authorities is such that we cannot be confident accommodation is being accurately categorised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by Housing Benefit departments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as exempt or otherwise.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For the time being Single Housing Benefit Extract data cannot be relied on even as a measure of the volum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e of supported exempt accommodation and the Housing Benefit expenditure upon it.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 35.85pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The amount of Housing Benefit claimed by people of working age in supported and sheltered housing in any local authority depends less on the proportion of supported and shelte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">red housing that currently counts as exempt accommodation than on the extent to which that local authority has provision for what in the Supporting People programme were known as the “socially excluded” groups.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-before:always"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Future responsibility for the cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> of support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ed and sheltered hou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ng</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government is expected shortly to publish another consultation paper on how to deal with the housing costs of people on low incomes living in supported and sheltered housing. This new paper is necessary because the previous </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">paper, published in 2011, appears to have met with widespread criticism – although it is not possible for us to judge this as the Government has never published an analysis of the responses it received.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We do not necessarily disagree with the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">view that the DWP would not be well placed to take over full responsibility for handling the housing costs of claimants living in supported housing from local authority Housing Benefit departments.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But the Government appears to be driven by the need to hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e a plan in place to cope with the intended shutdown of Housing Benefit departments by the end of 2017 – a deadline which may appear difficult to achieve given the slow roll-out to date of Universal Credit.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sitra feels it is important – given that the grea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t majority of supported housing in most authorities is for older people – that the discussion of the future does not start only from the basis of Universal Credit but must take account of the proposed Rent Credit within Pension Credit. However, it does not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appear the design of this has yet progressed very far.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not therefore clear whether or not the housing costs of older people in sheltered housing (with the possible exception of Extra Care sheltered housing) can simply be dealt with alongside the hou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing costs of older people generally. If so, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we recognise that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there would be some lower-tier authorities where there would be hardly any supported housing requiring specialist treatment outside of Pension Credit and Universal C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">redit – certainly not enough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for such authorities to develop and maintain expertise in assessing and meeting costs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government is, in our view, mistaken to think that upper-tier authorities are necessarily well-placed to take over some or all responsibility for handling the housi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng costs of claimants living in supported housing. As commissioners of care and support, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upper-tier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authorities have increasingly purchased these separately from accommodation and we see no evidence adult social care departments generally have any re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ason at present to understand these housing costs in any detail.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are therefore extremely apprehensive as to whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a transfer of responsibility of the kind the Government appears to favour will provide a secure future for the residents or providers of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supported housing, a section of the population everyone acknowledges are particularly vulnerable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>